    <h3 id="aka">AKA domain</h3>
    <p>An AKA domain creates a parallel version of a site (or domain) for our redirection software. This allows us to preview redirects before going live.</p>

    <h3 id="archive">Archive</h3>
    <p>An old URL that does not meet a user need. To users it shows a standard GOV.UK page with the option of viewing the old page on the National Archives or going to the organisation’s new GOV.UK homepage.
    </p>
    <h4>Example</h4>
    <%= link_to @example_archive.old_url, @example_archive.old_url %></p>

    <h3 id="cname">CNAME Record</h3>
    <p>Using a <code>CNAME</code> DNS record is one of the two ways of pointing a domain name at a server that hosts a website.</p>
    <h4>Example</h4>
    www.gov.uk has a CNAME record that points at www-gov-uk.map.fastly.net

    <h3 id="dns">DNS</h3>
    <p>The Domain Name System (DNS) connects domain names (eg www.gov.uk) with a server address.</p>
    <p>The switchover happens when the DNS entries for your site are changed to point at our servers, enabling our servers to redirect or show archive pages.</p>

    <h3 id="domain">Domain</h3>
    <p>A domain name (eg www.gov.uk) is used to reach a site. One or more domains can be used for a single site. Sub-domains are domains in their own right.</p>

    <h3 id="furl">Friendly URLs (FURLs)</h3>
    <p>A customised URL designed to be easily memorable to direct people at a specific page with a simple title, eg gov.uk/taxdisc.</p>
    <p>These are not picked up in log files or analytics so we need to know about these in advance.</p>

    <h3 id="global-archive">Global archive</h3>
    <p>All pages on a site are <a href="#archive">archived</a>.</p>

    <h3 id="global-redirect">Global redirect</h3>
    <p>All pages on a site are <a href="#redirect">redirected</a> to the same URL.</p>

    <h3 id="hits">Hits</h3>
    <p>Requests for a URL or document. This includes pages, images and file downloads.</p>

    <h3 id="host">Host, Hostname</h3>
    <p>In this context, a host or hostname is the same as a domain name.</p>

    <h3 id="a-record">A Record/IP Address</h3>
    <p>Using an <code>A</code> DNS record is one of the two ways of pointing a domain name at a server that hosts a website.</p>
    <h4>Example</h4>
    google.com has an A record that points at the IP address 62.253.3.88

    <h3 id="mapping">Mapping</h3>
    <p>A mapping is the relationship between an old URL and either a new URL or the decision to present an archive page to the user.</p>

    <h3 id="partial">Partial transition, Partial domain</h3>
    <p>In some situations it isn’t possible to switch an entire site over at once. This can happen in several situations:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>multiple organisations share a site</li>
      <li>some content on a site needs to remain available at that site</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 id="path">Path</h3>
    <p>The part of a URL immediately following the domain name. In the URL:<br /><code>https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations</code><br />the path is: <code>/government/organisations</code></p>

    <h3 id="protocol">Protocol</h3>
    <p>The first part of a URL, either <code>http</code> or <code>https</code>. All redirects and links to GOV.UK must use https.</p>

    <h3 id="query-parameters">Query parameters</h3>
    <p>The part of a URL written to be read by a computer. In the URL:<br /><code>https://www.gov.uk/?search=jobs&amp;type=1</code> the query parameters are: <code>search</code> and <code>type</code>.</p>

    <h4>Significant query parameters</h4>
    <p>In order to reduce the number of mappings for you to write and maintain, we identify the significant query parameters in use on your site, which lets us deduplicate many URLs. A query parameter is significant if changing it means a user sees different content.</p>

    <h3 id="redirect">Redirect</h3>
    <p>A redirect means automatically taking a user from the old URL they requested to the new one identified in the mapping. For example <code>http://www.bis.gov.uk</code> redirects to <code class="breakable">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-business-innovation-skills</code>
</p>
    <h4>Example</h4>
    <%= link_to @example_redirect.old_url, @example_redirect.old_url %><br />
    <span class="text-muted">redirects to</span>
    <%= link_to @example_redirect.new_url, @example_redirect.new_url %>

    <h3 id="site">Site</h3>
    <p>Usually the smallest unit of transition. Note that one or more domains can be used for a single site, often for historical reasons.</p>

    <p>An example site is: <%= link_to @example_site.default_host.hostname, site_path(@example_site) %></p>

    <h3 id="status-codes">(HTTP) Status codes</h3>
    <p>Examples of HTTP Status Codes are: 404, 410, 301, 200 and 502. In transition there are a few which are important. 301 is used for a redirect, 410 is used for archive, and 404 means that there isn’t a mapping for the old URL yet.</p>

    <table class="table table-bordered add-top-margin">
